WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:08.967
-[bugs chittering]
-[birds chirping]

2
00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.074
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-

3
00:00:24.024 --> 00:00:25.650
[young girl] Once upon a time…

4
00:00:34.909 --> 00:00:36.494
-[girl] Laura!
-[Laura grunts]

5
00:00:37.162 --> 00:00:38.329
[groans in frustration]

6
00:00:40.790 --> 00:00:42.542
Do you want dinner or not?

7
00:00:43.543 --> 00:00:45.545
[lively music playing]

8
00:00:46.337 --> 00:00:47.839
[Laura] Once upon a time.

9
00:00:48.423 --> 00:00:50.258
Pa and Ma

10
00:00:50.967 --> 00:00:52.677
and Mary and Laura

11
00:00:53.178 --> 00:00:57.098
left their house
in the Big Woods of Wisconsin.

12
00:00:57.932 --> 00:01:00.602
Ma was sad to leave our life behind.

13
00:01:00.685 --> 00:01:03.396
but Pa said it was getting too crowded.

14
00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:06.649
and we needed a fresh start in the West.

15
00:01:07.942 --> 00:01:11.738
Every day. the horses traveled
as far as they could.

16
00:01:12.238 --> 00:01:15.200
and Pa and Ma made camp in a new place.

17
00:01:17.911 --> 00:01:20.955
Finally. they came to the prairie.

18
00:01:21.456 --> 00:01:25.585
where there was nothing but grass
and waves of light and shadow

19
00:01:25.668 --> 00:01:27.712
and a giant sky.

20
00:01:30.298 --> 00:01:34.177
Every day and every night
was an adventure.

21
00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:35.261
[Mary] Let's go!

22
00:01:35.345 --> 00:01:36.721
[Laura] And they were happy

23
00:01:37.305 --> 00:01:40.809
because they were a family
and they were together.

24
00:01:40.892 --> 00:01:42.894
[fiddle music playing]

25
00:01:44.062 --> 00:01:48.650
♪ O whistle
And I'll come to you. my lad ♪

26
00:01:48.733 --> 00:01:54.030
♪ O whistle
And I'll come to you. my lad ♪

27
00:01:54.114 --> 00:01:59.035
♪ Tho' Father and Mother
And a' should gae mad ♪

28
00:01:59.119 --> 00:02:03.665
♪ O whistle
And I'll come to you. my lad ♪

29
00:02:08.086 --> 00:02:09.546
[fiddle music fades]

30
00:02:09.629 --> 00:02:11.714
[hopeful music playing]

31
00:02:12.298 --> 00:02:13.716
Almost there. Half Pint.

32
00:02:16.427 --> 00:02:20.223
♪ The Ingalls are coming
Hurrah. hurrah ♪

33
00:02:20.306 --> 00:02:23.476
♪ The Ingalls are coming to Kansas now ♪

34
00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:27.438
♪ The Ingalls are coming
Hurrah. hurrah ♪

35
00:02:27.522 --> 00:02:30.525
♪ The Ingalls are coming
Hurrah ♪

36
00:02:35.238 --> 00:02:37.657
[father] See?
Lots of wagons have crossed here.

37
00:02:39.450 --> 00:02:43.288
-Why would someone leave it here?
-Oh. too heavy. probably.

38
00:02:43.788 --> 00:02:45.582
[Laura] Can Jack ride inside?

39
00:02:46.833 --> 00:02:48.001
Just this once.

40
00:02:48.084 --> 00:02:50.086
[heartwarming music playing]

41
00:03:08.271 --> 00:03:09.355
[snorting]

42
00:03:11.316 --> 00:03:12.984
[horses whinny loudly]

43
00:03:13.067 --> 00:03:15.153
[creaking]

44
00:03:15.236 --> 00:03:16.362
[gasps]

45
00:03:17.322 --> 00:03:18.448
[horses neighing]

46
00:03:20.074 --> 00:03:21.826
-Take the reins.
-Pa!

47
00:03:21.910 --> 00:03:23.286
Charles!

48
00:03:23.369 --> 00:03:25.371
[dramatic music playing]

49
00:03:26.456 --> 00:03:27.498
[Charles gasping]

50
00:03:27.582 --> 00:03:28.666
[dog barking]

51
00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:31.336
[horses whinny frantically]

52
00:03:31.419 --> 00:03:32.295
[continues barking]

53
00:03:32.378 --> 00:03:34.339
[Charles grunting]

54
00:03:34.422 --> 00:03:35.422
[grunts]

55
00:03:38.343 --> 00:03:39.594
Don't let go!

56
00:03:40.094 --> 00:03:41.387
No! Jack!

57
00:03:44.974 --> 00:03:46.643
-[Mary] Jack!
-Jack!

58
00:03:46.726 --> 00:03:48.186
-[mother] Stay back.
-[Laura] Jack!

59
00:03:48.269 --> 00:03:49.520
-Laura. stay back!
-Jack!

60
00:03:49.604 --> 00:03:50.438
Jack!

61
00:03:50.521 --> 00:03:51.814
[Jack whining]

62
00:03:51.898 --> 00:03:52.899
[creaking]

63
00:03:54.275 --> 00:03:55.401
[creaking]

64
00:03:58.279 --> 00:03:59.572
[girls scream]

65
00:03:59.656 --> 00:04:00.740
[panting]

66
00:04:01.699 --> 00:04:03.034
[Laura] We have to move!

67
00:04:03.117 --> 00:04:05.119
[both grunting]

68
00:04:05.995 --> 00:04:07.664
[horse neighing frantically]

69
00:04:08.248 --> 00:04:09.832
-[Mary] Ma!
-[grunting]

70
00:04:09.916 --> 00:04:11.125
[mother] Girls. hold on!

71
00:04:11.209 --> 00:04:12.210
Move!

72
00:04:12.794 --> 00:04:13.795
[neighing]

73
00:04:13.878 --> 00:04:16.130
[grunting. yelling]

74
00:04:16.714 --> 00:04:17.799
-[grunts]
-[loud creaking]

75
00:04:24.138 --> 00:04:25.390
[music fades]

76
00:04:26.307 --> 00:04:28.309
[panting]

77
00:04:29.227 --> 00:04:30.227
Girls.

78
00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:31.271
[Mary exclaims]

79
00:04:31.354 --> 00:04:33.481
[tense music playing]

80
00:04:33.564 --> 00:04:35.566
[Mary and Laura breathing heavily]

81
00:04:39.696 --> 00:04:41.197
[panting]

82
00:04:44.409 --> 00:04:45.285
[tender music playing]

83
00:04:45.368 --> 00:04:46.661
[horses neighing]

84
00:04:46.744 --> 00:04:48.162
[Charles groans]

85
00:04:48.246 --> 00:04:50.123
[mother panting]

86
00:04:51.749 --> 00:04:53.751
[Charles panting]

87
00:04:54.294 --> 00:04:57.380
-[Mary] Jack! Jack!
-Are you all right? Are you hurt?

88
00:04:57.463 --> 00:05:00.550
-You okay? You all right?
-[Mary and Laura] Jack! Jack!

89
00:05:00.633 --> 00:05:02.302
-[Mary] Jack!
-Jack!

90
00:05:05.847 --> 00:05:06.848
-Jack!
-Jack!

91
00:05:07.515 --> 00:05:08.808
[retches]

92
00:05:08.891 --> 00:05:10.435
[Laura] Jack!

93
00:05:10.518 --> 00:05:11.686
[vomits]

94
00:05:11.769 --> 00:05:13.771
[groaning]

95
00:05:15.565 --> 00:05:17.567
[panting]

96
00:05:18.359 --> 00:05:20.361
[panting]

97
00:05:22.155 --> 00:05:24.365
[man] I saw your wagon
get caught in the chutes.

98
00:05:26.367 --> 00:05:27.493
Whoa.

99
00:05:27.577 --> 00:05:28.703
Everyone all right?

100
00:05:31.539 --> 00:05:34.208
I'm Dr. George Tann. May I take a look?

101
00:05:34.292 --> 00:05:35.292
[music fades]

102
00:05:35.835 --> 00:05:37.253
[Dr. Tann] This may sting a little.

103
00:05:38.254 --> 00:05:39.380
[winces]

104
00:05:41.632 --> 00:05:44.093
-[winces]
-It seemed like a good crossing.

105
00:05:44.177 --> 00:05:46.512
Spring rains make for fast waters.

106
00:05:47.096 --> 00:05:48.348
It's an easy mistake.

107
00:05:49.974 --> 00:05:51.309
You got a way with horses.

108
00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:55.480
You kept calm. got everybody to shore.

109
00:05:56.939 --> 00:05:57.939
Very fine work.

110
00:06:02.528 --> 00:06:05.281
-Keep 'em dry as best you can.
-Thank you.

111
00:06:05.782 --> 00:06:07.867
[Dr. Tann] Take it
you're headed to Independence.

112
00:06:07.950 --> 00:06:09.994
Not far now. just about a half a day.

113
00:06:10.078 --> 00:06:11.079
Once you get into town.

114
00:06:11.162 --> 00:06:14.123
see yourself to Henderson General Store
for the best prices.

115
00:06:14.957 --> 00:06:18.461
-Where can I find the land office?
-No. No land office. Not yet.

116
00:06:18.544 --> 00:06:21.464
You could probably find
Eli James at the Judson Hotel.

117
00:06:21.547 --> 00:06:24.509
He'll set you in the right direction
to stake a claim.

118
00:06:25.259 --> 00:06:26.260
[exhales]

119
00:06:27.261 --> 00:06:28.261
You know.

120
00:06:29.514 --> 00:06:33.643
most people come out west
with more hands. friends. family.

121
00:06:35.478 --> 00:06:36.521
Not all alone.

122
00:06:38.314 --> 00:06:39.524
It didn't work out.

123
00:06:42.735 --> 00:06:44.529
Hope you find what you're looking for.

124
00:06:44.612 --> 00:06:46.697
[melancholy music playing]

125
00:07:09.679 --> 00:07:10.888
What about the food?

126
00:07:12.765 --> 00:07:15.143
It's not all gone. but close to it.

127
00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:22.233
Forgive me.

128
00:07:32.452 --> 00:07:34.203
We'll make a feast of the last of it.

129
00:07:34.787 --> 00:07:39.083
Jack! Jack!

130
00:07:41.461 --> 00:07:42.503
Jack!

131
00:07:49.594 --> 00:07:51.804
[curious music playing]

132
00:07:56.392 --> 00:07:57.393
[woman in Osage] Come on.

133
00:07:58.102 --> 00:07:59.604
Stop spying.

134
00:08:06.068 --> 00:08:08.070
[horses nickering]

135
00:08:12.825 --> 00:08:13.993
[in English] Laura.

136
00:08:15.119 --> 00:08:16.579
Ma says come to dinner.

137
00:08:30.968 --> 00:08:32.136
[music fades]

138
00:08:35.181 --> 00:08:36.432
You missed breakfast.

139
00:08:45.399 --> 00:08:47.068
We need to be on our way.

140
00:08:47.944 --> 00:08:50.863
-We have to wait for Jack.
-[Charles] Jack's a good swimmer.

141
00:08:50.947 --> 00:08:54.242
He's probably just exploring the river
a little before he catches up with us.

142
00:08:54.325 --> 00:08:56.244
How will he find us?

143
00:08:56.327 --> 00:08:58.871
Easy. He'll follow your smell.

144
00:08:59.455 --> 00:09:02.291
[uplifting music playing]

145
00:09:13.344 --> 00:09:14.595
What are you doing?

146
00:09:15.471 --> 00:09:16.973
Leaving a trail for Jack.

147
00:09:22.937 --> 00:09:24.814
Cornbread is his favorite.

148
00:09:28.317 --> 00:09:29.402
[bleating]

149
00:09:44.292 --> 00:09:46.043
-[Charles grunts]
-[exhales sharply]

150
00:09:46.752 --> 00:09:47.837
It's so small.

151
00:09:47.920 --> 00:09:49.255
What we wanted. right?

152
00:09:50.006 --> 00:09:53.342
-Be the beginning of something.
-Come and find us when you're finished.

153
00:09:57.471 --> 00:09:59.765
-Don't forget the peppermint sticks.
-I won't.

154
00:10:00.349 --> 00:10:01.183
Come on.

155
00:10:01.267 --> 00:10:03.269
[music continues]

156
00:10:04.812 --> 00:10:07.148
[hammering]

157
00:10:07.231 --> 00:10:09.400
[pig squealing]

158
00:10:20.745 --> 00:10:22.747
[people chattering]

159
00:10:23.497 --> 00:10:24.498
[bell ringing]

160
00:10:24.582 --> 00:10:28.169
Hello. I'm Emily Henderson.
I don't think we've had the pleasure.

161
00:10:28.753 --> 00:10:31.464
Caroline Ingalls. Oh. I have a list.

162
00:10:32.506 --> 00:10:34.925
And also.
I'd like to mail these letters home.

163
00:10:35.009 --> 00:10:36.969
Oh. I'm sorry.
There's no post office here yet.

164
00:10:37.053 --> 00:10:38.929
There's no post office.
no church. no school.

165
00:10:39.013 --> 00:10:40.598
[mouths]

166
00:10:41.182 --> 00:10:43.225
We do have a very fine doctor. [chuckles]

167
00:10:44.101 --> 00:10:46.187
Just the list. then. Thank you.

168
00:10:46.687 --> 00:10:48.689
[piano music playing in the distance]

169
00:11:00.910 --> 00:11:02.912
[piano music playing]

170
00:11:06.207 --> 00:11:08.209
[people chattering]

171
00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:16.550
Excuse me. I'm looking for Eli James.

172
00:11:16.634 --> 00:11:18.052
What do we have here?

173
00:11:18.719 --> 00:11:19.845
Fresh face.

174
00:11:21.514 --> 00:11:24.892
Let me guess.
You're here to claim your promised land.

175
00:11:26.018 --> 00:11:28.396
[man] Oh. don't pay Mr. Kind here
any mind.

176
00:11:28.979 --> 00:11:30.064
[piano music stops]

177
00:11:30.147 --> 00:11:31.148
I'm Eli James.

178
00:11:32.441 --> 00:11:35.611
Ingalls. Dr. Tann said
you're the man to ask about a claim.

179
00:11:35.695 --> 00:11:39.240
-You got family with you. Mr. Ingalls?
-My wife and daughters.

180
00:11:39.323 --> 00:11:40.408
Hm.

181
00:11:40.491 --> 00:11:42.493
No brothers. No sons.

182
00:11:43.369 --> 00:11:46.664
See yourself over to the mill.
Sam Parker keeps a map of the claims.

183
00:11:46.747 --> 00:11:49.208
Unofficial. but it'll send you
in the right direction.

184
00:11:49.291 --> 00:11:51.127
Too bad there's nothing but scraps left.

185
00:11:51.210 --> 00:11:55.131
-[Eli] There's plenty of land left.
-Plenty of wolves too. [howls]

186
00:11:55.214 --> 00:11:56.774
-[men laugh]
-No need to act like fools.

187
00:12:01.303 --> 00:12:04.765
-Welcome to Independence. Mr. Ingalls.
-Thank you.

188
00:12:04.849 --> 00:12:06.100
[Laura] What do you want?

189
00:12:06.183 --> 00:12:08.978
Peppermint? Gumdrops? Lemon drops?

190
00:12:09.061 --> 00:12:11.063
[lighthearted music playing]

191
00:12:16.569 --> 00:12:18.028
My ribbons floated away.

192
00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:20.780
So?

193
00:12:21.198 --> 00:12:23.743
[Mary] So. Ma wants us to be civilized.

194
00:12:24.243 --> 00:12:28.664
Ribbons are civilized.
even out here in the middle of nowhere.

195
00:12:28.748 --> 00:12:30.416
I'd rather have this.

196
00:12:30.499 --> 00:12:32.460
Why? You barely know how to read.

197
00:12:36.005 --> 00:12:37.381
I know how to read.

198
00:12:38.090 --> 00:12:38.966
Take it back.

199
00:12:39.049 --> 00:12:41.260
-Even though you're old enough.
-[grunts]

200
00:12:41.343 --> 00:12:43.846
[Mary gasping]

201
00:12:50.561 --> 00:12:53.355
[emotional music playing]

202
00:13:00.905 --> 00:13:02.865
[Emily] Caleb.
they're waiting on those packages.

203
00:13:05.701 --> 00:13:06.702
[music fades]

204
00:13:06.786 --> 00:13:08.662
Will you all be staying
at the hotel tonight?

205
00:13:08.746 --> 00:13:12.291
-[Caroline] We prefer to camp.
-Keep a close eye on your girls out there.

206
00:13:12.792 --> 00:13:16.754
Wolves and men
are equally likely to steal them away.

207
00:13:16.837 --> 00:13:20.132
Wolves are just wild creatures.
Keep your distance. Don't leave food out.

208
00:13:20.216 --> 00:13:22.510
-And you'll be fine.
-Just a little friendly advice.

209
00:13:23.385 --> 00:13:24.385
[Emily] Your bill.

210
00:13:28.808 --> 00:13:30.408
Well. everything has to come a long way.

211
00:13:30.434 --> 00:13:32.895
-I promise you the prices are fair.
-I'm sure they are.

212
00:13:33.395 --> 00:13:36.690
-We could open you a line of credit?
-No. Thank you.

213
00:13:37.191 --> 00:13:41.529
I will just have to leave off
the coffee and the bacon.

214
00:13:42.655 --> 00:13:43.739
And the eggs.

215
00:13:44.907 --> 00:13:48.744
And the sugar. And the ginger root.
So sorry for the trouble.

216
00:13:48.828 --> 00:13:50.579
No. it's no trouble at all.

217
00:14:01.298 --> 00:14:02.424
Do you wanna sing?

218
00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:10.975
[cues horses]

219
00:14:16.564 --> 00:14:18.566
[horses neighing]

220
00:14:20.985 --> 00:14:22.987
[crickets chirping]

221
00:14:33.038 --> 00:14:34.373
You can have my ribbons.

222
00:14:35.332 --> 00:14:37.084
I don't want your ribbons.

223
00:14:38.335 --> 00:14:39.837
You made me look stupid.

224
00:14:39.920 --> 00:14:41.463
'Cause of that boy?

225
00:14:42.172 --> 00:14:43.799
He didn't even say hi.

226
00:14:44.383 --> 00:14:47.678
Besides. I thought you were
in love with dumb Charlie Stone.

227
00:14:47.761 --> 00:14:50.848
Well. I'm never gonna see him again. am I?

228
00:14:52.850 --> 00:14:55.936
You don't care that we left.
because you didn't have any friends.

229
00:14:56.604 --> 00:14:57.604
I did.

230
00:15:02.610 --> 00:15:03.777
[Mary huffs]

231
00:15:04.695 --> 00:15:06.196
[sighs]

232
00:15:07.072 --> 00:15:09.742
[Laura] Come on. Jack.
I know you'll find us.

233
00:15:09.825 --> 00:15:11.827
[heartfelt music playing]

234
00:15:18.083 --> 00:15:19.168
[sighs]

235
00:15:22.463 --> 00:15:23.797
You take this.

236
00:15:25.507 --> 00:15:27.217
I've got my axe and my knife.

237
00:15:27.885 --> 00:15:29.803
We need another gun or another dog.

238
00:15:29.887 --> 00:15:33.223
Put 'em on the list. I'll be back
before sunset with a place to call home.

239
00:15:34.892 --> 00:15:36.477
-[cues horses]
-[horse nickers]

240
00:15:46.445 --> 00:15:49.949
[Mary and Laura chuckling]

241
00:16:04.505 --> 00:16:06.006
Ma. look!

242
00:16:06.799 --> 00:16:08.384
[music fades]

243
00:16:08.467 --> 00:16:10.260
She's an Indian doll. right?

244
00:16:10.844 --> 00:16:12.680
What do you think her name is?

245
00:16:13.263 --> 00:16:15.641
Can I keep her? Please?

246
00:16:17.142 --> 00:16:18.644
You can sew up the rips

247
00:16:19.478 --> 00:16:20.854
and use my ribbons.

248
00:16:23.649 --> 00:16:24.649
Fine.

249
00:16:25.192 --> 00:16:27.194
[insects chittering]

250
00:16:38.414 --> 00:16:39.581
Why isn't Pa back?

251
00:16:43.627 --> 00:16:45.254
Probably just stopped to hunt.

252
00:16:48.716 --> 00:16:49.883
He didn't take the gun.

253
00:16:52.177 --> 00:16:54.179
[tender music playing]

254
00:17:32.176 --> 00:17:33.927
-[dog whining]
-[Laura gasps]

255
00:17:34.553 --> 00:17:35.553
Jack?

256
00:17:36.805 --> 00:17:38.807
[whining continues]

257
00:17:44.354 --> 00:17:45.731
[rustling]

258
00:17:48.442 --> 00:17:50.444
[tense music playing]

259
00:17:51.737 --> 00:17:53.072
[growling]

260
00:17:55.032 --> 00:17:56.032
[Laura gasps]

261
00:18:04.416 --> 00:18:05.876
[growling]

262
00:18:05.959 --> 00:18:08.087
[tense music building]

263
00:18:13.634 --> 00:18:15.135
-[gun fires]
-[wolf whimpering]

264
00:18:16.303 --> 00:18:17.429
Get away from her!

265
00:18:17.513 --> 00:18:19.598
[growls]

266
00:18:20.516 --> 00:18:22.976
[Laura panting]

267
00:18:23.060 --> 00:18:24.353
[Laura gasps]

268
00:18:25.938 --> 00:18:27.648
[continues growling]

269
00:18:27.731 --> 00:18:28.941
[breathing heavily]

270
00:18:31.985 --> 00:18:32.820
Go!

271
00:18:32.903 --> 00:18:34.113
[snarls]

272
00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:36.281
[music fades]

273
00:18:38.534 --> 00:18:40.536
[breathing shakily]

274
00:18:40.619 --> 00:18:42.746
[melancholy music playing]

275
00:18:52.256 --> 00:18:53.882
[birds chirping]

276
00:18:53.966 --> 00:18:56.218
[footsteps approaching]

277
00:18:57.136 --> 00:18:58.720
-Easy.
-[breathing heavily]

278
00:18:58.804 --> 00:18:59.888
It's just me.

279
00:19:02.891 --> 00:19:03.891
Where were you?

280
00:19:04.393 --> 00:19:06.770
I lost track of time.
so Pet and I had to make camp.

281
00:19:07.271 --> 00:19:10.190
But I found the most beautiful.
perfect piece of land.

282
00:19:10.274 --> 00:19:11.483
Wait until you see it.

283
00:19:14.111 --> 00:19:15.279
Hm?

284
00:19:15.362 --> 00:19:19.283
-Should we have breakfast. be on our way?
-Make your own breakfast.

285
00:19:22.911 --> 00:19:24.788
[breathes deeply]

286
00:19:25.539 --> 00:19:27.708
Laura almost got eaten by a wolf.

287
00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:36.592
[hopeful music playing]

288
00:19:42.389 --> 00:19:43.640
[horse grunting]

289
00:19:48.854 --> 00:19:49.938
[nickering]

290
00:19:56.904 --> 00:19:58.906
[Mary and Laura laughing]

291
00:20:03.619 --> 00:20:06.788
All right. so house goes here.
Garden. here.

292
00:20:07.414 --> 00:20:08.540
Stable. there.

293
00:20:09.249 --> 00:20:10.249
And a swing.

294
00:20:11.084 --> 00:20:14.046
And next spring is wheat and corn.
as much as we can plant.

295
00:20:17.841 --> 00:20:19.426
[Mary sniffles]

296
00:20:30.145 --> 00:20:32.481
Well. what do you think?

297
00:20:33.357 --> 00:20:37.277
My sister said I was a fool to leave
everything and everyone I ever knew

298
00:20:37.361 --> 00:20:38.820
and follow you into the dark.

299
00:20:40.239 --> 00:20:41.239
Here we are.

300
00:20:46.161 --> 00:20:47.412
But here we are.

301
00:20:48.664 --> 00:20:51.083
[fiddle music playing]

302
00:20:52.334 --> 00:20:53.835
[Caroline laughs]

303
00:20:53.919 --> 00:20:55.921
[Mary and Laura laughing]

304
00:21:00.842 --> 00:21:02.722
[Caroline. Mary. Laura]
♪ Roll on. silver moon ♪

305
00:21:02.761 --> 00:21:05.430
♪ Point the traveler's way ♪

306
00:21:05.514 --> 00:21:09.559
♪ While the nightingale's song
Is in tune ♪

307
00:21:09.643 --> 00:21:14.189
♪ I never. never more
With my true love will stray ♪

308
00:21:14.273 --> 00:21:19.278
♪ By the soft silver beams. gentle moon ♪

309
00:21:23.365 --> 00:21:27.828
♪ As the hart on the mountain
My lover was brave ♪

310
00:21:27.911 --> 00:21:29.913
♪ So noble and manly… ♪

311
00:21:30.497 --> 00:21:31.873
Laura Elizabeth Ingalls!

312
00:21:33.125 --> 00:21:34.668
I'm gonna get you!

313
00:21:34.751 --> 00:21:36.878
♪ And he loved me full dear ♪

314
00:21:36.962 --> 00:21:40.757
♪ Oh. my Edwin. his equal was never ♪

315
00:21:40.841 --> 00:21:43.135
[both grunting]

316
00:21:46.972 --> 00:21:47.973
[laughs]

317
00:21:55.772 --> 00:21:56.772
[song ends]

318
00:21:59.609 --> 00:22:00.609
[grunts]

319
00:22:01.862 --> 00:22:03.196
[exhales] I'm awake.

320
00:22:05.365 --> 00:22:06.533
[exhales]

321
00:22:07.409 --> 00:22:08.409
You sleep.

322
00:22:08.994 --> 00:22:11.747
I'll leave Mary to look after you.
take Laura to help me.

323
00:22:14.833 --> 00:22:16.960
[horse nickering. snorting]

324
00:22:24.301 --> 00:22:27.179
[hopeful music playing]

325
00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:07.469
[grunting]

326
00:23:11.765 --> 00:23:13.445
Yeah. That's good. That's good. That's it.

327
00:23:14.059 --> 00:23:15.059
[pants]

328
00:23:15.936 --> 00:23:16.978
[Charles grunts]

329
00:23:17.062 --> 00:23:18.605
Take a break. Half Pint.

330
00:23:21.608 --> 00:23:23.610
[music fades]

331
00:23:26.738 --> 00:23:28.740
[footsteps approaching]

332
00:23:32.494 --> 00:23:33.494
Hello.

333
00:23:37.749 --> 00:23:38.750
Oh.

334
00:23:39.751 --> 00:23:41.753
Oh! She's yours?

335
00:23:44.798 --> 00:23:48.343
[in Osage] She took my doll.

336
00:23:48.844 --> 00:23:53.723
I doubt she took your doll.

337
00:23:53.807 --> 00:23:56.184
You lost it. remember?

338
00:23:56.268 --> 00:23:57.394
All the tears?

339
00:23:58.645 --> 00:24:00.814
[in English] I found her
under a rock in the mud.

340
00:24:00.897 --> 00:24:04.609
Ma sewed up the rips in her dress.
You can keep the button.

341
00:24:05.193 --> 00:24:06.862
I'm Laura. by the way.

342
00:24:06.945 --> 00:24:08.488
[Charles] Charles Ingalls.

343
00:24:08.572 --> 00:24:11.533
We're building a house nearby.
just over the ridge.

344
00:24:12.451 --> 00:24:13.535
Maybe we're neighbors.

345
00:24:15.495 --> 00:24:18.623
[in Osage] Tell Laura thank you.

346
00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:21.042
[in English] Thank you.

347
00:24:27.048 --> 00:24:28.048
[clicks tongues]

348
00:24:33.555 --> 00:24:36.266
[Laura] She was the same girl
I saw at the river.

349
00:24:37.225 --> 00:24:38.685
And in town.

350
00:24:38.768 --> 00:24:40.187
And the doll was hers.

351
00:24:40.770 --> 00:24:43.607
Can we find out where they live?
Can we go visit?

352
00:24:43.690 --> 00:24:46.109
-We don't need to know them.
-Why?

353
00:24:48.236 --> 00:24:51.573
-We don't need to go looking for trouble.
-What kind of trouble?

354
00:24:53.074 --> 00:24:54.201
Ma.

355
00:24:55.744 --> 00:24:56.744
what kind of trouble?

356
00:24:57.496 --> 00:24:59.039
Trouble with the Indians.

357
00:24:59.122 --> 00:25:02.334
But they live here.
Why would there be trouble?

358
00:25:03.043 --> 00:25:05.837
And why would we come
all the way to the prairie

359
00:25:05.921 --> 00:25:07.339
if we didn't want to know them?

360
00:25:07.422 --> 00:25:10.675
I've been through enough war.
I don't need another at my doorstep.

361
00:25:10.759 --> 00:25:13.428
War? With the Indians?

362
00:25:13.512 --> 00:25:14.721
No. of course not.

363
00:25:18.433 --> 00:25:20.727
There were some hard times in the north.
This is Kansas.

364
00:25:20.810 --> 00:25:22.145
The country's different now.

365
00:25:24.689 --> 00:25:26.066
I'd like to know 'em too.

366
00:25:28.693 --> 00:25:30.946
[woman in Osage] You should have
run them off.

367
00:25:31.029 --> 00:25:33.240
This land still belongs to us.

368
00:25:33.323 --> 00:25:37.118
I don't think there's any sense
in making enemies.

369
00:25:37.202 --> 00:25:41.122
And now our daughter thinks
she's going to be friends with them.

370
00:25:41.706 --> 00:25:43.124
[in English] Why shouldn't we?

371
00:25:45.377 --> 00:25:47.170
You see? You see. cousin?

372
00:25:47.254 --> 00:25:50.632
She's openhearted. that's all.
Just like her big sister was.

373
00:26:00.725 --> 00:26:02.227
I didn't mean to upset her.

374
00:26:03.853 --> 00:26:04.854
It's all right.

375
00:26:05.647 --> 00:26:06.982
It's nice to remember.

376
00:26:08.984 --> 00:26:12.320
Tell me about your trip. What sort
of land is the government offering?

377
00:26:12.821 --> 00:26:15.865
Rocky. hilly. lots of scrub and oak.

378
00:26:15.949 --> 00:26:18.076
I don't think most
of it's any good for farming.

379
00:26:18.159 --> 00:26:20.287
but I saw lots of game. lots of water.

380
00:26:21.037 --> 00:26:23.957
White Sun was… not impressed.

381
00:26:25.959 --> 00:26:28.587
Maybe land like that
would keep the settlers out.

382
00:26:29.087 --> 00:26:32.257
-Maybe they wouldn't be interested in it.
-Maybe.

383
00:26:34.843 --> 00:26:36.970
[man] Would you stay or go
if it comes to that?

384
00:26:39.222 --> 00:26:41.099
I'd hate to lose everything we built here.

385
00:26:41.975 --> 00:26:45.228
[melancholy music playing]

386
00:26:49.649 --> 00:26:51.401
[upbeat music playing]

387
00:27:02.996 --> 00:27:04.789
Three. two. one.

388
00:27:06.958 --> 00:27:08.001
[Caroline grunts]

389
00:27:20.305 --> 00:27:21.305
[Mary gasps]

390
00:27:21.806 --> 00:27:25.310
-Give it back. Give it.
-I thought they floated away.

391
00:27:26.186 --> 00:27:28.730
I was wrong. They were in my pocket.

392
00:27:32.901 --> 00:27:34.110
I need more water.

393
00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:36.320
[grunts]

394
00:27:37.947 --> 00:27:39.574
[grunts. sighs]

395
00:27:42.369 --> 00:27:43.369
Need a rest?

396
00:27:43.870 --> 00:27:44.870
I'm fine.

397
00:27:45.330 --> 00:27:46.330
[grunts softly]

398
00:27:47.082 --> 00:27:48.208
[Charles grunts]

399
00:27:52.921 --> 00:27:54.756
[Caroline grunting]

400
00:27:55.507 --> 00:27:56.758
-[screaming]
-[bone snaps]

401
00:27:56.841 --> 00:27:57.676
[Charles] Caroline!

402
00:27:57.759 --> 00:27:59.511
[screams. groans]

403
00:28:01.471 --> 00:28:02.806
-[Charles grunts]
-[screams]

404
00:28:04.516 --> 00:28:05.725
[grunts. pants]

405
00:28:05.809 --> 00:28:09.145
-[groans] How bad is it?
-We need to stop the bleeding.

406
00:28:09.688 --> 00:28:11.314
[breathing shakily]

407
00:28:11.398 --> 00:28:13.233
-Mary. go get some clean cloth. Hurry.
-Okay.

408
00:28:14.067 --> 00:28:16.027
[Caroline] It's okay. It's okay. I'm okay.

409
00:28:17.862 --> 00:28:19.364
[winces]

410
00:28:21.199 --> 00:28:22.199
[Caroline groans]

411
00:28:25.829 --> 00:28:28.373
[groans]

412
00:28:30.291 --> 00:28:31.835
I need to ride for Dr. Tann.

413
00:28:31.918 --> 00:28:35.338
-No. Please don't go.
-The sooner I go. the sooner I'll be back.

414
00:28:35.422 --> 00:28:37.674
-The girls will take care of you. right?
-[Mary] Yes.

415
00:28:37.757 --> 00:28:38.757
Okay.

416
00:28:41.094 --> 00:28:42.387
[Mary breathing shakily]

417
00:28:43.179 --> 00:28:44.179
It's okay.

418
00:28:51.062 --> 00:28:52.605
[exhales shakily]

419
00:28:59.779 --> 00:29:02.282
Maybe Laura can tell us
one of her stories?

420
00:29:02.365 --> 00:29:04.367
[melancholy music playing]

421
00:29:07.954 --> 00:29:09.497
Once upon a time.

422
00:29:10.415 --> 00:29:11.833
in the Big Woods.

423
00:29:13.460 --> 00:29:16.379
Ma and Pa and Mary and Laura

424
00:29:17.505 --> 00:29:20.341
rode through the sugar snow
to Grandma's house.

425
00:29:23.386 --> 00:29:24.929
It was maple season.

426
00:29:26.848 --> 00:29:30.351
and everyone was coming
for a moonlight dance in the barn.

427
00:29:32.228 --> 00:29:33.688
Pa played his fiddle.

428
00:29:35.231 --> 00:29:38.568
and Ma wore her green dress
with the tiny flowers.

429
00:29:40.069 --> 00:29:44.949
and Grandma piled maple cakes so high
you could hardly see over the tops of...

430
00:29:45.033 --> 00:29:46.701
I wish we'd never left.

431
00:29:47.202 --> 00:29:49.913
I wish we had stayed
with Grandma and Grandpa

432
00:29:49.996 --> 00:29:52.123
and Aunt Eliza and Uncle Peter.

433
00:29:52.207 --> 00:29:53.541
and… and all my friends.

434
00:29:53.625 --> 00:29:56.711
and the trees and owls.
and we'd still have Jack.

435
00:29:56.795 --> 00:29:59.464
[Mary sobs quietly]

436
00:30:04.844 --> 00:30:06.638
Staying wasn't that simple.

437
00:30:09.682 --> 00:30:11.392
No one came to say goodbye.

438
00:30:14.395 --> 00:30:16.648
Why didn't anyone come to say goodbye?

439
00:30:22.403 --> 00:30:24.572
The important thing
is that we're together.

440
00:30:27.700 --> 00:30:30.119
As long as we're together.
everything will be fine.

441
00:30:33.039 --> 00:30:35.041
[Mary sobs]

442
00:30:44.634 --> 00:30:46.636
[horses approaching]

443
00:30:59.732 --> 00:31:02.026
Gotta change the bandage every day.

444
00:31:06.990 --> 00:31:09.242
And you're gonna
have to stay off your feet.

445
00:31:12.745 --> 00:31:14.205
Any more pains?

446
00:31:17.876 --> 00:31:18.876
Any…

447
00:31:20.169 --> 00:31:21.379
Any bleeding?

448
00:31:26.426 --> 00:31:27.426
A little.

449
00:31:27.802 --> 00:31:28.802
but it stopped.

450
00:31:32.348 --> 00:31:33.600
I haven't told Charles yet.

451
00:31:37.437 --> 00:31:38.437
I see.

452
00:31:43.443 --> 00:31:46.237
[Caroline] He said he was happy
with just the girls. but

453
00:31:47.739 --> 00:31:49.240
all men want sons.

454
00:31:53.202 --> 00:31:54.245
[scoffs]

455
00:31:55.288 --> 00:31:57.457
After all this time. why now?

456
00:32:00.501 --> 00:32:02.545
How am I supposed to have a baby out here?

457
00:32:04.547 --> 00:32:05.965
What kinda luck is that?

458
00:32:08.092 --> 00:32:11.137
I set the bones. closed the wound.
and gave her something for the pain.

459
00:32:11.888 --> 00:32:13.514
But even if she weren't injured.

460
00:32:13.598 --> 00:32:15.642
your wife can't be doing
this kind of work.

461
00:32:16.267 --> 00:32:19.020
not with a… a baby coming.

462
00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:25.652
If there aren't any friends or family.
you'll have to hire help.

463
00:32:27.362 --> 00:32:29.656
I burned through
every penny making the trip.

464
00:32:30.239 --> 00:32:33.701
I don't have any money
until the mortgage payments start coming.

465
00:32:33.785 --> 00:32:36.537
I've seen entire families
freeze to death out here.

466
00:32:37.580 --> 00:32:38.581
starve to death.

467
00:32:39.248 --> 00:32:41.960
get taken by fever. wolves. madness.

468
00:32:42.043 --> 00:32:45.964
It is a myth
that men can make it out here alone.

469
00:32:46.839 --> 00:32:49.384
It's a pretty story. nothing more.

470
00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:52.428
You find help

471
00:32:53.471 --> 00:32:54.764
any way you can.

472
00:32:56.975 --> 00:32:58.977
[tender music playing]

473
00:33:21.457 --> 00:33:22.875
I've lost so many.

474
00:33:24.085 --> 00:33:26.254
I just didn't want you
to be disappointed again.

475
00:33:29.173 --> 00:33:30.299
I'll fix this.

476
00:33:31.217 --> 00:33:32.217
I promise.

477
00:33:34.887 --> 00:33:37.807
[hopeful music playing]

478
00:34:04.625 --> 00:34:06.127
[knocking]

479
00:34:06.210 --> 00:34:07.210
Hello?

480
00:34:08.296 --> 00:34:09.297
Anyone home?

481
00:34:09.380 --> 00:34:11.382
[music fades]

482
00:34:22.935 --> 00:34:23.935
[man] Morning.

483
00:34:25.897 --> 00:34:29.817
-Or is it. uh… is it later than morning?
-I'm sorry. I didn't mean to intrude.

484
00:34:29.901 --> 00:34:32.320
No matter. Rare to get a visitor.

485
00:34:33.863 --> 00:34:36.407
Except. uh… except for these strays.

486
00:34:36.991 --> 00:34:39.577
-You like cats?
-[Charles] I'm more of a dog person.

487
00:34:40.078 --> 00:34:42.497
We lost ours on the trail. unfortunately.

488
00:34:43.081 --> 00:34:46.292
Charles Ingalls.
I don't think we were properly introduced.

489
00:34:46.375 --> 00:34:47.376
John Edwards.

490
00:34:48.044 --> 00:34:49.337
Dr. Tann sent me.

491
00:34:50.254 --> 00:34:53.633
I'm building a house. He said
you might be willing to trade some work.

492
00:34:54.592 --> 00:34:57.011
I've got my wife and daughters with me.
Two girls.

493
00:34:57.095 --> 00:35:00.348
They're just about the same age as yours.
by the looks of it.

494
00:35:00.973 --> 00:35:02.266
[purring]

495
00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:06.729
Where do you come from. Mr. Edwards?

496
00:35:07.355 --> 00:35:08.355
Tennessee.

497
00:35:08.773 --> 00:35:13.820
[sniffles] Thing is. I haven't. uh…
I haven't quite decided if I'll stay. so…

498
00:35:14.570 --> 00:35:16.656
Well. I promise
we'll do fast work together.

499
00:35:17.532 --> 00:35:19.200
Build you a house so snug and warm

500
00:35:19.283 --> 00:35:22.453
that when you send for your family.
it'll be a very happy home.

501
00:35:22.537 --> 00:35:23.663
Hm.

502
00:35:26.916 --> 00:35:28.042
What are their names?

503
00:35:29.168 --> 00:35:30.168
Your girls?

504
00:35:32.088 --> 00:35:33.339
My wife's Caroline.

505
00:35:33.422 --> 00:35:34.340
[tense music playing]

506
00:35:34.423 --> 00:35:36.384
My daughters are Mary and Laura.

507
00:35:41.222 --> 00:35:42.640
I didn't mean to offend.

508
00:35:42.723 --> 00:35:43.599
[horse neighing]

509
00:35:43.683 --> 00:35:45.101
A happy home. you say. hm?

510
00:35:46.018 --> 00:35:47.395
I should be on my way.

511
00:35:49.981 --> 00:35:50.981
[man] Edwards.

512
00:35:55.903 --> 00:35:58.364
Came to pay you back
for the nails I borrowed.

513
00:35:58.865 --> 00:36:02.368
Some of our persimmons for your trouble.

514
00:36:04.871 --> 00:36:06.164
[grunting]

515
00:36:06.247 --> 00:36:07.582
[both grunt]

516
00:36:07.665 --> 00:36:09.375
-[Charles yells]
-[Mr. Edwards grunts]

517
00:36:10.084 --> 00:36:11.627
[Charles panting]

518
00:36:14.172 --> 00:36:15.339
[music fades]

519
00:36:15.423 --> 00:36:16.674
[snoring]

520
00:36:16.757 --> 00:36:17.884
[cat meowing]

521
00:36:20.720 --> 00:36:22.054
He'll sleep it off.

522
00:36:23.097 --> 00:36:25.725
He always does. [sighs]

523
00:36:26.726 --> 00:36:28.811
I don't know where you come from.
Mr. Ingalls.

524
00:36:29.770 --> 00:36:32.370
But more often than not.
this country calls a certain kind of man.

525
00:36:33.482 --> 00:36:35.568
Some are desperate and out of luck.

526
00:36:35.651 --> 00:36:37.904
Some have been scraped raw
by war and poverty.

527
00:36:39.363 --> 00:36:42.658
Some are just destructive
and cruel and hard by nature.

528
00:36:44.869 --> 00:36:45.912
Step carefully.

529
00:36:49.373 --> 00:36:50.373
I'll do that.

530
00:36:52.710 --> 00:36:53.711
William Mitchell.

531
00:36:55.504 --> 00:36:56.923
Thank you. Mr. Mitchell.

532
00:37:06.682 --> 00:37:09.393
[horse snorts. nickers]

533
00:37:28.454 --> 00:37:29.454
Waiting for me?

534
00:37:36.128 --> 00:37:38.089
[voice breaking] I didn't hold him
tight enough.

535
00:37:40.383 --> 00:37:41.384
I let go.

536
00:37:44.220 --> 00:37:46.264
And he jumped into the water.

537
00:37:48.099 --> 00:37:49.475
[inhaling shakily]

538
00:37:49.558 --> 00:37:51.811
I should have held on tighter.

539
00:37:54.647 --> 00:37:56.023
It wasn't your fault.

540
00:37:58.401 --> 00:37:59.944
Jack jumped in to save me.

541
00:38:01.195 --> 00:38:02.989
I should've known better
than to cross there.

542
00:38:05.700 --> 00:38:07.952
I should have known better
about a lot of things.

543
00:38:10.162 --> 00:38:12.039
Ma said he's not coming back.

544
00:38:20.214 --> 00:38:21.465
Hope is everything.

545
00:38:23.092 --> 00:38:24.302
It's the only thing.

546
00:38:26.012 --> 00:38:27.263
Don't give up on him.

547
00:38:31.809 --> 00:38:33.102
Don't give up on us.

548
00:38:39.191 --> 00:38:40.191
I won't.

549
00:38:41.319 --> 00:38:43.321
[emotional music playing]

550
00:38:51.454 --> 00:38:53.456
[crickets chirping]

551
00:38:59.795 --> 00:39:01.797
[footsteps approaching]

552
00:39:12.933 --> 00:39:13.976
Mmm.

553
00:39:14.810 --> 00:39:16.410
Did you find someone to trade work with?

554
00:39:17.730 --> 00:39:18.731
Not just yet.

555
00:39:19.523 --> 00:39:21.525
[music fades]

556
00:39:25.112 --> 00:39:26.447
If you wanna go back.

557
00:39:27.323 --> 00:39:29.325
we can start off
as soon as you feel strong enough.

558
00:39:30.951 --> 00:39:34.872
We don't have money for the trip.
We need supplies. new horses.

559
00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:39.543
-And we don't have a house to go back to.
-Your brother could take us in.

560
00:39:40.044 --> 00:39:42.171
[Caroline] There's no going back. Charles.

561
00:39:43.297 --> 00:39:45.132
Not after everything that happened.

562
00:39:46.467 --> 00:39:48.761
Not for a long time anyway.
and certainly not as beggars.

563
00:39:53.182 --> 00:39:54.182
[sighs]

564
00:40:07.696 --> 00:40:09.016
Do you remember the night we met?

565
00:40:10.658 --> 00:40:14.036
-Harvest dance at the Anderson farm.
-[Caroline] We danced all night.

566
00:40:14.954 --> 00:40:19.125
While we were dancing. it started to snow.
so you carried me home on your back.

567
00:40:19.208 --> 00:40:20.626
You wore a blue dress.

568
00:40:25.214 --> 00:40:28.008
You were so wild and strange.

569
00:40:29.510 --> 00:40:32.012
All the girls were madly in love with you.

570
00:40:32.805 --> 00:40:33.889
I didn't notice.

571
00:40:33.973 --> 00:40:34.973
[chuckles softly]

572
00:40:40.563 --> 00:40:42.398
You could've chosen any of 'em…

573
00:40:45.317 --> 00:40:46.485
But you chose me.

574
00:40:50.322 --> 00:40:53.075
And I knew in that moment.
I would follow you anywhere.

575
00:40:55.161 --> 00:40:56.704
And look where it got you.

576
00:41:00.708 --> 00:41:02.168
This place scares me.

577
00:41:05.087 --> 00:41:06.714
I won't pretend it doesn't.

578
00:41:08.174 --> 00:41:10.092
But it was my choice to come.

579
00:41:12.803 --> 00:41:16.015
I said yes because I believe in you.

580
00:41:17.933 --> 00:41:19.226
Your light.

581
00:41:19.977 --> 00:41:22.313
Your dreams. Your imagination.

582
00:41:24.690 --> 00:41:27.568
I want our children to have
a better life than the one we had.

583
00:41:29.778 --> 00:41:30.905
[inhales deeply]

584
00:41:31.530 --> 00:41:32.948
And what if I was wrong?

585
00:41:35.910 --> 00:41:37.119
What if it isn't better?

586
00:41:41.582 --> 00:41:42.582
And what if

587
00:41:43.876 --> 00:41:47.296
this is where we finally become
who we were meant to be?

588
00:41:49.590 --> 00:41:52.134
What if this is where
your son is finally born? [laughs]

589
00:41:56.430 --> 00:41:58.349
How will we ever know till we try?

590
00:42:02.019 --> 00:42:03.270
Sell the books.

591
00:42:04.855 --> 00:42:06.524
my father's pocket watch.

592
00:42:07.483 --> 00:42:08.859
my silver combs.

593
00:42:09.527 --> 00:42:11.111
anything else we have to spare.

594
00:42:14.573 --> 00:42:15.573
The fiddle.

595
00:42:20.204 --> 00:42:21.288
Sell it all.

596
00:42:21.372 --> 00:42:22.372
[sobs]

597
00:42:22.831 --> 00:42:24.833
[mournful fiddle music playing]

598
00:42:28.128 --> 00:42:29.672
[sniffling]

599
00:42:58.325 --> 00:43:01.412
Maybe they didn't know
that we were leaving.

600
00:43:03.581 --> 00:43:06.292
Maybe they're all waiting
for us to come back.

601
00:43:16.802 --> 00:43:17.803
[music fades]

602
00:43:20.806 --> 00:43:22.808
[barking in the distance]

603
00:43:29.773 --> 00:43:31.775
[barking continues]

604
00:43:32.484 --> 00:43:34.486
[upbeat music playing]

605
00:43:34.570 --> 00:43:36.572
[panting]

606
00:43:42.620 --> 00:43:43.620
[Laura] Jack?

607
00:43:52.796 --> 00:43:54.214
[barking]

608
00:44:01.096 --> 00:44:04.350
-Hey! Jack! Jack! Jack!
-[whimpering]

609
00:44:06.268 --> 00:44:07.269
You found us.

610
00:44:09.271 --> 00:44:10.314
Jack.

611
00:44:16.236 --> 00:44:18.030
[music fades]

612
00:44:18.113 --> 00:44:19.698
Thought he might be yours.

613
00:44:20.282 --> 00:44:22.242
Pa says you lost a dog up on the trail.

614
00:44:23.452 --> 00:44:24.870
Are you Mary or are you Laura?

615
00:44:27.581 --> 00:44:29.249
Jack doesn't like strangers.

616
00:44:29.333 --> 00:44:31.460
[Mr. Edwards] We had a little talk
on the way up here.

617
00:44:32.044 --> 00:44:33.671
Missed his family. he said.

618
00:44:34.338 --> 00:44:35.338
[Charles] Laura!

619
00:44:36.382 --> 00:44:37.382
Pa!

620
00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:39.301
Take Jack. Go back to the tent.

621
00:44:39.385 --> 00:44:42.179
Stay inside till I tell you
you can all come back. You understand?

622
00:44:45.516 --> 00:44:47.101
[Jack barking]

623
00:44:49.937 --> 00:44:51.021
[Laura] Mary!

624
00:44:51.105 --> 00:44:52.105
[Jack barks]

625
00:44:53.107 --> 00:44:54.775
[Mary gasps] Jack!

626
00:44:55.275 --> 00:44:57.277
[heartwarming music playing]

627
00:44:58.654 --> 00:45:00.197
-[Mary laughs]
-[whimpering]

628
00:45:00.781 --> 00:45:03.200
How did you know he would find us?

629
00:45:03.826 --> 00:45:05.369
I didn't know.

630
00:45:05.869 --> 00:45:06.954
I just hoped.

631
00:45:07.037 --> 00:45:10.457
[Jack panting. whimpering]

632
00:45:12.126 --> 00:45:14.336
I wanna apologize for yesterday.

633
00:45:15.879 --> 00:45:17.214
Ashamed of my poor manners.

634
00:45:17.297 --> 00:45:18.298
[music fades]

635
00:45:18.966 --> 00:45:22.386
Thank you. but there's no need.
You can be on your way.

636
00:45:24.638 --> 00:45:26.181
Thing is. Mr. Ingalls.

637
00:45:27.141 --> 00:45:28.934
I'd like to help you build your house.

638
00:45:30.060 --> 00:45:33.021
Those girls are gonna need a roof
over their heads before the snows come.

639
00:45:33.981 --> 00:45:34.981
Or the wolves.

640
00:45:36.150 --> 00:45:38.110
What kinda fool would I be to trust you?

641
00:45:41.280 --> 00:45:42.280
Yeah.

642
00:45:46.118 --> 00:45:49.204
See. I. uh… I had a Laura too.

643
00:45:51.623 --> 00:45:53.041
Laura and Abigail.

644
00:45:58.422 --> 00:45:59.882
And they'd have loved it here.

645
00:46:01.842 --> 00:46:03.135
I mean. the birds.

646
00:46:03.927 --> 00:46:04.970
flowers.

647
00:46:05.471 --> 00:46:06.472
sky.

648
00:46:08.807 --> 00:46:10.934
Have you ever seen such a sky?

649
00:46:18.942 --> 00:46:20.235
Let me make things right.

650
00:46:30.496 --> 00:46:32.206
I can't pay. I can only trade.

651
00:46:34.374 --> 00:46:35.709
Yeah. so he said.

652
00:46:40.547 --> 00:46:42.466
Start first thing tomorrow morning.

653
00:46:43.175 --> 00:46:44.593
First yours. then mine.

654
00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:53.018
So you decided to stay?

655
00:46:53.685 --> 00:46:58.065
Well. if a man with so much to lose
is willing to risk it. why shouldn't I?

656
00:46:58.565 --> 00:47:02.694
-What do you mean? What risk?
-We're all just speculating on this land.

657
00:47:02.778 --> 00:47:03.987
Anything could happen.

658
00:47:04.071 --> 00:47:07.157
That's not true. It's open for settlement.
I read it in the newspapers.

659
00:47:07.241 --> 00:47:09.952
There's flyers everywhere in Wisconsin.
Free land.

660
00:47:10.035 --> 00:47:11.035
No. not this land.

661
00:47:11.995 --> 00:47:15.541
This is Osage land.
Everything here belongs to them.

662
00:47:16.124 --> 00:47:18.126
[pensive music playing]

663
00:47:19.962 --> 00:47:22.172
But the men in town said
they'd bring a land office...

664
00:47:22.256 --> 00:47:25.300
They're speculating.
hoping that the government's gonna step in

665
00:47:25.384 --> 00:47:26.552
and force the Osages out.

666
00:47:28.971 --> 00:47:32.057
Now. the Osage are out there now.
They're huntin'. but they will be back.

667
00:47:33.183 --> 00:47:35.894
And then you'll see there's nothin' free
about this land at all.

668
00:47:38.021 --> 00:47:40.148
Hey. no risk. no reward. right?

669
00:47:41.358 --> 00:47:43.151
I mean. isn't that why we're all here?

670
00:47:43.694 --> 00:47:45.404
To make a new America?

671
00:47:46.822 --> 00:47:48.198
Whatever that might be.

672
00:47:50.325 --> 00:47:53.078
I'll see you in the mornin'.
bright and early.

673
00:47:53.161 --> 00:47:55.163
[hopeful music playing]

674
00:48:14.641 --> 00:48:15.767
[Laura] Go. Jack!

675
00:48:17.394 --> 00:48:19.229
[Jack barking]

676
00:48:19.313 --> 00:48:22.274
[Mary and Laura laughing]

677
00:48:23.442 --> 00:48:25.444
Did you find someone
to help build the house?

678
00:48:26.904 --> 00:48:27.905
Yes.

679
00:48:30.240 --> 00:48:32.284
Then we'll be safe from all the wolves.

680
00:48:33.118 --> 00:48:34.036
Safe and sound.

681
00:48:34.119 --> 00:48:38.332
And we'll get to stay
with the grass and sky.

682
00:48:40.083 --> 00:48:41.793
This will be our new forever.

683
00:48:42.461 --> 00:48:43.378
Come on.

684
00:48:43.462 --> 00:48:45.464
[music continues]

685
00:48:49.426 --> 00:48:51.970
[music builds]

686
00:48:54.389 --> 00:48:56.725
[music intensifies]

687
00:48:56.808 --> 00:48:57.808
[music ends]

688
00:48:58.310 --> 00:49:00.312
[closing theme music playing]

689
00:50:22.102 --> 00:50:23.311
[music ends]

689
00:50:24.305 --> 00:51:24.406
